**who —** Ptahhotep — vizier to Pharaoh Djedkare Isesi and named author of the Maxims of Ptahhotep — counsel on justice, restraint, truth (ma'at), and right conduct

**what —** vizier to Pharaoh Djedkare Isesi and named author of the Maxims of Ptahhotep — counsel on justice, restraint, truth (ma'at), and right conduct

**where —** AMP · The Greek Mirror — Egypt · Memphis · Egypt (Old Kingdom, 5th Dynasty)  Framework inputs: the world's philosophers by year and location; the three classical pillars  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** Egypt's male anchor, and the first man by the elder date. Honest seam: the Maxims survive only in much-later copies (the Papyrus Prisse, Middle Kingdom), and 'philosopher' here means sage of wisdom-literature.

**how —** Seated in the Amphitheater of the World's Philosophers — Anchor Zero, by year and location.

**◌ the mythos —** Egypt's male anchor, and the first man by the elder date. Honest seam: the Maxims survive only in much-later copies (the Papyrus Prisse, Middle Kingdom), and 'philosopher' here means sage of wisdom-literature. an anchor of the Egypt house in the amphitheater of philosophers

